men is quite possible, for the recension referred to belonged no doubt
to this period; but no positive arguments beyond agreement in name and
country can be urged in support of it. Fabricius proposed to identify
our Hesychius with the author of the famous Greek Lexicon, which is
still extant. But this identification is now commonly rejected; and the
author of the lexicon is regarded as a pagan, who lived in Alexandria
during the latter part of the fourth century. See Smith’s *Dict. of
Greek and Roman Biography* and Smith and Wace’s *Dict. of Christ. Biog.
s.v.*

